    <section id="neuroscience" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Neuroscience: What Intelligence Looks Like in the Brain</h2>

      <p>Neuroimaging has provided a more granular picture of what <em>g</em> corresponds to in the brain, and it is not localized in the way that pop neuroscience once implied.</p>

      <p>Higher intelligence is associated with greater <strong>global efficiency of the brain's network architecture</strong> — more effective communication between distributed brain regions, rather than simply a larger or more active prefrontal cortex. A 2025 meta-analysis of neuroimaging studies found that brain-wide connectivity patterns predict cognitive performance, with connectivity across the default mode, frontoparietal, and salience networks all contributing.</p>

      <p>The parieto-frontal integration theory (P-FIT) of intelligence proposes that efficient information transfer along fronto-parietal pathways — connecting sensory and association areas with prefrontal executive circuits — is the structural basis of <em>g</em>. People with higher IQ show more myelin-rich white matter tracts connecting these regions, faster neural transmission speeds, and lower metabolic cost per cognitive operation — the brain equivalent of a more fuel-efficient engine.</p>

      <p>Processing speed, which is one of the components IQ tests measure, appears to be a proxy for this neural efficiency: how quickly the brain can execute the operations that cognitive tasks require. This processing speed advantage compounds across complex tasks that require many such operations in sequence.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="honest-summary" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Honest Summary</h2>

      <p>IQ is a real, valid, and useful measurement of something important. The something important is not intelligence as an essence but rather cognitive performance across abstract, school-relevant tasks, which predicts a meaningful range of outcomes across a human lifetime. The correlation with <em>g</em> is genuine. The predictive value is genuine. The genetics are real but substantially less deterministic than the popular framing implies.</p>

      <p>What IQ is not: a complete inventory of cognitive capacity, a ceiling on potential, a stable fixed property unresponsive to environment, or a morally meaningful human classification. The century of treating it as all of these things produced outcomes ranging from the merely inaccurate to the genuinely catastrophic.</p>

      <p>The most honest thing to say about intelligence is that it is a wide and varied territory, partially mapped by a tool that was designed to be useful in educational settings and became something much larger through misapplication and ambition. The tool still has value in its original domain. The territory is considerably more interesting, and considerably more accessible, than the number alone suggests.</p>
    </section>

